BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:TW1YC_xFxpyi9H3OPwrju
SUMMARY:Figure/Ground: New Criteria
DTSTAMP:20260406T054325Z
DTSTART:20260417T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Figure/Ground: New Criteria is inspired by cultural historian S
	arah Lewis’s concept of “groundwork aesthetics\,” exploring figure-ground 
	relationships and their connection to social tension. It builds on Lewis’s
	 work\, which—set against the expansion of Stand Your Ground laws across t
	he United States since 2005\, laws that broadly define rights to use letha
	l self-defense against perceived threats—describes a range of artistic int
	erventions that reimagine “the literal and figurative meaning of ground.” 
	Primarily featuring works from the Henry collection created in the twenty-
	first century\, Figure/Ground reflects a period in which hard-won civil ri
	ghts and claims to self-determination have been eroded across the US\, dis
	proportionately affecting Black\, Brown\, LGBTQ\\+\, and other marginalize
	d communities.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/figure-gro
	und-new-criteria/17923441/2026-04-17T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civ
	ic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/figure-ground-new-criteri
	a/17923441/2026-04-17T00
LOCATION:Henry Art Gallery\, 15th Ave NE & 41st St\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:fVxR7Kf274PSRqqiRwBVd
SUMMARY:Beyond Mysticism: The Modern Northwest
DTSTAMP:20260406T054325Z
DTSTART:20260417T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:image: Drift No. 2\, 1936\, Malcolm M. Roberts\, American\, 191
	3-1990\, tempera on board\, 25 1/2 x 20 5/8 in.\, Seattle Art Museum\, Eug
	ene Fuller Memorial Collection\, 37.103\, © Malcolm M. Roberts\, photo: Sc
	ott Leen.\n\nInspired by the region’s natural beauty and rapidly changing 
	city\, this exhibition showcases artists who told the raw story of Seattle
	 in the 20th century. By sharing the Pacific Northwest’s perspective throu
	gh trending art styles—including Social Realism\, Surrealism\, and Abstrac
	t Expressionism—these artists offered a unique take on Modernist art and c
	hallenged the “mystic” label ascribed to their works.\n\nSpearheading the 
	movement were local icons Mark Tobey\, Kenneth Callahan\, Guy Anderson\, a
	nd Morris Graves—but the range and breadth of Pacific Northwest art goes b
	eyond the “Big Four” of the Northwest School. Featuring more than 150 piec
	es\, this exhibition showcases works that investigate the complexities of 
	daily life in the region. Whether applying an ecocritical lens or producin
	g dreamy and uncanny visuals\, these artists expressed the duality of the 
	natural world and city life to warn of the environmental and social impact
	s of industrialization.\n\nFrom Malcolm Roberts to Kenjiro Nomura\, learn 
	how Northwest artists applied their regional perspective to broader artist
	ic developments to create a new form of American Modernism.\n\nThe exhibit
	ion is accompanied by a fully illustrated catalogue authored by Theresa Pa
	panikolas\, SAM’s Ann M. Barwick Curator of American Art.\n\nhttps://seato
	day.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-modern-northwest/183
	08126/2026-04-17T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/beyond-mysticism-the-mode
	rn-northwest/18308126/2026-04-17T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:yH26BMrDVPOOyX4Gn2pjN
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260406T054325Z
DTSTART:20260417T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-17T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-04-17T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:y0ISWJ_u-KceZZVzJ01ae
SUMMARY:Samantha Yun Wall: What We Leave Behind
DTSTAMP:20260406T054325Z
DTSTART:20260417T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Samantha Yun Wall’s new paintings use overlapping silhouettes o
	f female figures as portals to unknown spaces and different temporal realm
	s. Impetus for the new body of work is a Korean folk tale in which the Pas
	que flower is symbolic of a grandmother who passed away without the loving
	 care of her grandchildren. It is a story of melancholy\, loss\, and remem
	brance. The delicate hair on the flower’s stem differentiates it\, and the
	 artist gives the plant a surreal aspect in some of her paintings\, replac
	ing the flower’s center with a watchful eye.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we-leave-behind/18026187/2026-0
	4-17T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we
	-leave-behind/18026187/2026-04-17T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:2aWOhQqO93gx2LdUkKXEV
SUMMARY:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light
DTSTAMP:20260406T054325Z
DTSTART:20260417T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Anila Quayyum Agha: Geometry of Light invites you to become par
	t of the art. Agha\, a Pakistani American artist\, animates spaces with he
	r large-scale sculptural installations. Suspended from the ceiling\, Agha’
	s steel cubes are laser-cut with intricate designs that project geometric 
	shadows onto the visitor. She draws on both the light and dark of her own 
	life\, using South Asian art practices to convey the gender discrimination
	 she faced growing up as a young girl in Pakistan. An in-depth exploration
	 of Islamic architecture\, art\, and identity\, this is the first solo exh
	ibition of a Pakistani American artist in SAM’s 90-year history. Agha is c
	arving a name out for herself in the art world—visit the Seattle Asian Art
	 Museum for an immersive and illuminating experience.\n\nhttps://seatoday.
	6amcity.com/events/#/details/anila-quayyum-agha-geometry-of-light/16795597
	/2026-04-17T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/anila-quayyum-agha-geomet
	ry-of-light/16795597/2026-04-17T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:YC_pKvjKSDFUvOVeId4qY
SUMMARY:Kameelah Janan Rasheed: we leak\, we exceed
DTSTAMP:20260406T054325Z
DTSTART:20260417T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Kameelah Janan Rasheed \\(b. 1985\, East Palo Alto\, CA\; lives
	 and works in Brooklyn\, NY\\) is a self-described “learner” who creates m
	ulti-media works that explore the poetics-pleasures-politics of Black know
	ledge production\, information technologies\, \\[un\\]learning\, and belie
	f formation. She often integrates found images and words alongside her own
	 writing to create collaged wall installations and experimental video work
	s. Across her work\, Rasheed investigates the revision and life cycles of 
	text\, embracing expanded and embodied forms of writing and reading.\n\nwe
	 leak\, we exceed will activate the unique volume and multiple vantage poi
	nts of the Henry’s double-height gallery\, drawing together threads from p
	hysics\, Black critical thought\, and information theory to create an imme
	rsive environment that interrogates the spatial and social implications of
	 compression. A common process used in data storage\, spatial organization
	\, and information systems\, compression abbreviates and collapses complex
	 ideas into more simplified forms. Rasheed questions the way compression c
	omes at the cost of nuance and creates unrecoverable losses. She draws par
	allels between the compression of information and the containment of peopl
	e\, both physically and through the structuring and defining of identities
	. Through a network of video\, sound\, and architectural mark-making\, Ras
	heed proposes alternatively what she calls “an embrace of Black excess and
	 expansion” as a liberatory practice.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/even
	ts/#/details/kameelah-janan-rasheed-we-leak-we-exceed/16417090/2026-04-17T
	00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/kameelah-janan-rasheed-we
	-leak-we-exceed/16417090/2026-04-17T00
LOCATION:Henry Art Gallery\, 15th Ave NE & 41st St\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:pF0Iztft2yfTcoh-iljBD
SUMMARY:Springing Forward: Brunch for Black Economic Brilliance
DTSTAMP:20260406T054325Z
DTSTART:20260417T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Experience the Central District Community Preservation and Deve
	lopment Authority \\(CDCPDA\\) benefit brunch: Springing Forward: Brunch f
	or Black Economic Brilliance.\n\nNow in its second year\, this annual gath
	ering brings together more than 200 visionaries—professionals\, philanthro
	pists\, policymakers\, and community leaders—united by a shared commitment
	 to advancing Black economic empowerment in Seattle’s Central District and
	 beyond. \n\nAnchored in the themes: Collaborate. Sustain. Thrive.\n\nThe 
	brunch creates a dynamic space for meaningful connection\, shared learning
	\, and forward-looking action. The program will highlight current tenants\
	, key partnerships\, and community activations\, while also providing impo
	rtant updates on the progress of the McKinney Center for Community and Eco
	nomic Development—and a look ahead at what’s to come for the future of thi
	s vital project.\n\nGuests will engage directly with CDCPDA staff and boar
	d members\, as well as tenants of the McKinney Center\, a cornerstone comm
	unity hub driving inclusive economic growth. In partnership with Amazon’s 
	Black Employee Network\, this event moves beyond celebration to the intent
	ional cultivation of Black excellence and long-term community sustainabili
	ty. Join us for a meaningful experience that goes beyond traditional netwo
	rking—one rooted in collaboration\, resilience\, and collective progress. 
	Your presence helps fuel transformative impact and strengthens the foundat
	ion for a thriving\, equitable future.\n\nAttendee | $150.00﻿ ﻿Full access
	 to the brunch\, keynote\, and networking. Your ticket directly supports t
	he McKinney Center and community-rooted development in the Central Distric
	t.\n\nVendor Table | $175.00\n\nTable your business or organization during
	 the first hour of the event. Includes one attendee ticket.\n\nFull Table 
	\\(8 seats\\) | $1\,200.00\n\nBring your team or clients. Includes 8 indiv
	idual tickets — a savings of $1\,000 vs. individual pricing. Guest details
	 can be submitted after purchase.\n\nBe part of the movement. Together\, w
	e spring forward—collaborating\, sustaining\, and thriving.\n\nOur Emcee\n
	\nTraeAnna Holiday\, a true Seattleite\, has watched her city change in ma
	ny ways. She started training in media from the young age of 9 and continu
	ed through school up to Howard University and University of Washington. Th
	rough studying abroad multiple times\, gaining her degree in Communication
	s and Urban Studies\, and being displaced by gentrification\, she's now fu
	eled to tell her neighborhood's stories through film and media. She found 
	a home for this work at Converge Media as a two-time Emmy award winning Me
	dia Personality\, TV Show Host and Producer\, with her daily talk show\, T
	he Day With Trae\, and other productions. As Communications Director for W
	ashington state’s Office of Equity\, she is able to bring her knowledge an
	d enthusiasm for communications and the community to the state level. Flou
	rishing with her style\, passion\, and drive\, she dynamically creates imp
	act media throughout her work\, and helps the next generation find their v
	oice in the world of media. \n\nOur Keynote Speaker\n\nLaNesha McCoy is a 
	skilled public historian with over 20 years experience leading African Ame
	rican museums and history initiatives. She is Executive Director of BlackP
	ast.org\, the world’s largest online encyclopedia on Black history which w
	as founded by Dr. Quintard Taylor. Prior\, she served as President & CEO o
	f the Northwest African American Museum from 2017 to 2023 where she led st
	rategic planning\, recordsetting fundraising\, and innovative programming.
	 LaNesha is Past National President of the Association of African American
	 Museums Board of Directors\, only the sixth woman in history to serve in 
	that capacity. A member of the International Council of Museums\, she has 
	studied museums globally in Kenya\, Ghana\, South Africa\, England\, Germa
	ny\, and Israel. An ordained clergy\, LaNesha is Assistant Pastor at the h
	istoric New Hope Missionary Baptist Church in Seattle's Central District a
	nd Executive Administrator of the New Hope Community Development Institute
	\, which is focused on building affordable housing for people of color. Ne
	ver forgetting her roots or the many mentors that shaped her life\, she no
	w has three master's degrees and is currently a PhD Candidate at the Unive
	rsity of Washington where she teaches and researches African American educ
	ational history. She's a mentor and advocate\, leading initiatives to supp
	ort education.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/springing-
	forward-brunch-for-black-economic-brilliance/18474520/2026-04-17T00\n\nFro
	m SEAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/springing-forward-brunch-
	for-black-economic-brilliance/18474520/2026-04-17T00
LOCATION:Amazon Frontier\, 2205 7th Ave\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
